<ServiceLayout 
  name="ADHD Testing"
  description="Comprehensive ADHD assessments and diagnostics for children, teens, and adults"
>
  <h2>What is ADHD Testing?</h2>
  <p>
    Attention-Deficit/Hyperactivity Disorder (ADHD) is a neurodevelopmental condition that affects focus, impulse control, and executive functioning. Our comprehensive ADHD testing provides accurate diagnosis and personalized insights to help you or your child thrive with the right support and accommodations.
  </p>

  <h2>Who Should Get Tested?</h2>
  <ul>
    <li>Children struggling with focus, organization, or completing schoolwork</li>
    <li>Teens experiencing academic challenges despite strong abilities</li>
    <li>Adults with lifelong patterns of difficulty with time management and focus</li>
    <li>Individuals seeking clarity about symptoms or needing documentation for accommodations</li>
  </ul>

  <h2>What to Expect</h2>
  <p>
    Our evaluation process is comprehensive and considers the whole person. We use evidence-based assessments, rating scales, and clinical interviews to gather a complete picture. The process typically includes:
  </p>
  <ul>
    <li>Clinical interview and developmental history review</li>
    <li>Standardized ADHD rating scales and questionnaires</li>
    <li>Cognitive and attention testing</li>
    <li>Assessment of executive functioning skills</li>
    <li>Comprehensive feedback session and detailed written report</li>
  </ul>

  <h2>Why Choose Us?</h2>
  <p>
    Our team provides <strong>strengths-based, affirming assessments</strong> that recognize ADHD as a difference in brain wiring, not a character flaw. We understand how ADHD presents differently across ages, genders, and life circumstances, and we take a holistic approach to evaluation.
  </p>
  <p>
    Whether you need diagnosis, educational or workplace accommodations, or clarity about treatment options, we're here to provide thorough, compassionate evaluation and ongoing support.
  </p>

  <blockquote>
    "ADHD is not about lacking attention. It's about directing it differently."
  </blockquote>
</ServiceLayout>